However, telling the truth is not a crime.
In his letter, Snowden wrote that he believed that support from the international community could persuade the U.S. government to drop the criminal charges against him.
As part of the complaint filed by the U.S. Department of Justice, he is charged with espionage and theft of state property.
German Interior Minister Hans-Peter Friedrich told Zeit Online: “If Mr Snowden is willing to speak to German officials, we will make it possible.”
Relations between the United States and Germany have been put to a severe test following complaints that the NSA had wiretapped German Chancellor Angela Merkel’s mobile phone.
Thomas Oppermann, the MP who heads the parliamentary group overseeing the foreign intelligence services, said that if there was a chance to hear Mr. Snowden as a witness “without endangering him and completely ruining relations with the United States,” one should take advantage of it.
German Green MP Ströbele posted a photo of himself with Snowden on his Twitter account.
During his visit to Russia, he was accompanied by two German journalists.
Mr Ströbele said that according to the lawyer of the former NSA consultant, Mr Snowden would not be able to return to Russia if he left the country.
If Snowden were to testify in Germany, he would have to be assured that he would be “safe” there, the MP said.
Snowden wrote in his letter that he was the subject of a “serious and sustained” campaign of persecution that forced him to leave his country.
However, he said he had been encouraged by the global reaction to “my act of political expression.”
Citizens around the world as well as senior officials – including in the United States – have deemed the disclosure of an inexplicable system of permanent surveillance to be of public utility.
The letter makes an offer of cooperation with the German authorities “when the difficulties of this humanitarian situation have been resolved”.
