Frontier Airlines plans to charge for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge up to $100 for passengers carrying hand luggage on its flights.
Frontier Airlines plans to start charging up to $100 for hand luggage and $2 for a coffee or soda, although in its announcement Wednesday, it indicated that passengers could take the unopened can with them on the descent of the plane.
The new hand luggage fee applies to bags stored in the upper compartment, so small bags installed under the seat will always be free.
Frontier said it would charge $25 if fees were paid in advance and $100 if travelers only paid once at the boarding gate.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said the $100 was planned to encourage travelers to pay the fee in advance.
“We don’t want to charge that price,” she explained.
Airlines began charging for first and second checked baggage in 2008.
Passengers trying to avoid these charges would put as much stuff as they could into the hand luggage stored in the upper compartments, so there was often no room in these compartments.
These fees are a way to ensure that passengers carry fewer things on board.
O'Malley said that these new fees will not really be used to raise money.
It’s about making Frontier’s most loyal customers understand that it’s becoming increasingly difficult to find room in the upper compartments.
Passengers who purchase their tickets on the airline’s website will not have to pay.
Thus, a passenger queuing at a Frontier boarding gate could carry a bag for free, while the next person in the queue might have to pay $100 for a similar bag.
O'Malley explained that Frontier's site and check-in procedures are changing to ensure passengers are aware of these charges before they arrive at the gate.
Frontier’s hand baggage charges will not apply until the summer, although no dates have been set.
Passengers often groan about baggage and other charges, but airlines love them.
They believe that the costs of handling luggage are significant and that passengers who want this service should pay for it.
Many people on Wall Street see the addition of baggage charges as a sign that airlines are charging enough to cover the cost of air travel after years of losses.
However, many of them did not pay for luggage.
Spirit Airlines Inc. applied the first hand luggage fee three years ago, and low-cost carrier Allegiant followed suit a little later.
The only other airline imposing such fees is Hungarian Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors the surcharge fees.
He estimated, in a December 2011 report, that Spirit’s hand baggage charges earned $50 million a year.
Sorensen, a former Midwest Airlines executive, recently traveled on Spirit and wondered what he would find at the boarding gate as passengers discovered the unusual hand luggage charges imposed by the airline.
“I’ve never seen such a smooth boarding procedure in my entire professional career,” he said.
I expected to see grinding teeth and a fight break out at the door.
The plane was full, he added, “passengers got on board at lightning speed.”
Frontier also acts as Spirit and charges a $2 fee for a coffee, tea, soda or fruit juice.
Frontier said passengers who drink a soda or fruit juice can take the unopened can with them, and those who drink coffee can be reserved free of charge.
It will always distribute water free of charge.
US Airways briefly tried to charge for drinks in 2008 but backtracked seven months later after passengers complained and no other major airlines followed.
Frontier’s decision to charge hand baggage fees when passengers do not purchase their tickets directly from the airline is its latest effort to encourage customers to go to its site.
Airlines pay online travel sellers like Orbitz $10 to $25 for each ticket sold.
This prompted all airlines to encourage passengers to buy directly from them instead of going to an online travel agency.
However, Frontier went further in this area.
In September, it began offering only half the loyalty miles to customers who purchased their tickets through an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, she reduced mileage premiums by 25% on a trip.
Thus, a 1,000-mile Frontier trip purchased from an online travel agency would earn 250 miles.
It also allows passengers to choose their seat in advance only if they buy their ticket directly from Frontier’s website.
Frontier has a loyal clientele in her hometown of Denver, but her business declines and she loses money.
Revenue fell 9% and its flight capacity declined nearly 13% in the first quarter, according to financial results released Wednesday by its parent company, Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
Republic tried to straighten out Frontier's finances by selling the airline.
The NSA calls an “internal error” and not hackers for the failure of its site
The shadowy National Security Agency said Friday that it was a bug that had caused its public site to crash for a few hours, not hackers as some had claimed online.
“NSA.gov remained inaccessible for a few hours tonight due to an internal error that occurred during a planned update,” the spy agency said in an emailed statement.
The problem will be solved tonight.
Allegations that the failure was due to a distributed denial of service (DSD) attack are false.
Earlier this evening, online server trackers noted that the NSA site had been down for at least 6 hours, and some users still cannot access the site.
Earlier, an NSA spokesman told ABC News that the agency’s sensitive internal network was “not at all” compromised.
No classified information is in jeopardy, the spokesman said.
At least one group of online hacktivists claimed to be responsible for the failure of the NSA site by a DSD attack.
DSD attacks aim to flood a targeted site until the servers are overloaded and the site collapses.
The cyber-tactics are not very sophisticated and the attacks are not intended to penetrate the internal network of the targeted system.
The once top-secret NSA, once dubbed the “No Such Agency,” has come under fire and been heavily criticized in recent months following a wave of revelations about its extensive communications surveillance programs at home and abroad – part of the NSA’s secret files stolen from the agency and leaked by former NSA consultant Edward Snowden.
This growing controversy around the agency has sparked much speculation that tonight’s incident was the result of a targeted cyber-operation.
The Delta Centre-Ville now closed
The Delta Centre-Ville hotel closed its doors Thursday in Montreal, after 36 years of existence.
The investment fund that owned the building sold it to developers who will turn it into student residences.
Three hundred and fifty people worked at the hotel.
Of these, 200 have not yet found a new job.
Delta promises not to let its employees down.
Employers came to meet with employees directly on site, and employees were met individually to assess their needs.
“This support will continue for the next six months,” says Félix Bisson, regional director of labour relations at Delta Hotels.
The closure of the Delta is taking place in a very competitive hotel market.
The investment fund that owned this building had choices to make.
Either it reinvested in the building to continue operating it, so there were investments of tens of millions while the competition is very fierce, there are many new hotels that have appeared in Montreal.
“Or he was selling it to someone else and that’s what happened,” says Paul Arsenault, who holds the Transat Tourism Chair at the UQAM School of Management Sciences.
Other hotels in Montreal will also be converted in the coming months, such as the Crown Plaza, which will become a seniors’ residence.
In the meantime, four hotel projects totalling nearly 600 rooms will be launched within two years.
CEO of Titan: "Goodyear Amiens acquisition project starts with zero employees"
After throwing the towel with a bang in January for the partial takeover of the Goodyear site in Amiens-Nord promised to close, Maurice Taylor, the CEO of the American tire manufacturer Titan, today declares himself ready to save 333 jobs out of the 1,137 that counts the factory.
Arnaud Montebourg, Minister of Productive Recovery, had already announced it, Monday, October 21.
After giving up the plant purchase project in January, you come back today.
