Bombardier profit down as aircraft deliveries and orders decline
Bombardier Inc, a Canadian aircraft and rail manufacturer, reported a 15% drop in its net profit on Thursday, under pressure from lower orders and aircraft deliveries during the third quarter and contractual issues in its Trains division.
Montreal-based Bombardier has also failed to provide in-flight test data for its all-new CSeries aircraft or information on whether the aircraft will meet its ambitious commercial commissioning schedule by September.
After the test plane's maiden flight about a month and a half ago, it flew only three times, and the question then arose as to whether the test phase was on track.
The results did not live up to expectations and the share price fell by 8% on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerksen, an analyst with National Bank Financial, lowered his rating on Thursday from “superperformance” to “sector performance” due to the low potential for the stock market to rise in the next quarter or two.
“Although the decline in aircraft deliveries was largely anticipated, we are really disappointed by the profit margin in the Transport division,” Cameron Doerksen said in a note to customers.
We believe Bombardier will register new orders for its CSeries aircraft as the flight test program progresses.
However, if no new orders are announced in the coming months, we expect the market to become more skeptical about the program.
Bombardier hopes that the CSeries family of aircraft will be able to catapult it into the lower segment of a market now dominated by Boeing and Airbus.
The first test aircraft was unveiled in March and flew for the first time in September after months of delay.
However, the number of firm orders for CSeries aircraft has so far been modest at 177. It appears that potential buyers are waiting for the results of the flight tests to validate the company's claims regarding the energy efficiency and savings potential of the new airliner.
At present, the company has registered a total of 403 orders and purchase commitments with 15 customers and operators.
Pierre Beaudoin, President and Chief Executive Officer, is confident that Bombardier will achieve its 300 firm orders target before the first aircraft enters commercial service.
Leaders also reassured analysts and the media on Thursday that the program was progressing according to schedule.
"The test aircraft did not stay on the ground longer than expected," Beaudoin said in a conference call, adding that ground tests and software updates were planned during the aircraft's downtime.
Each manufacturer plans differently.
We decided to make a first flight and provide an update period, and that's what we did.
This will happen again throughout the flight program.
The second of the five test aircraft is expected to fly in the coming weeks, the others will follow shortly thereafter, the company said.
Yet analysts are skeptical that the first customer could fly a CSeries aircraft only 12 months after its maiden flight.
Bombardier said it was evaluating the timeline for entry into service and will provide new information in the coming months.
