Yet one interesting point has been forgotten in this interpretation of an old dusty tale.
Why should an independent Scotland follow Europe's instructions, in fact?
Why trade the yoke of London for the yoke of Brussels, especially now?
Here is the real news about Europe: the great post-war plan to unify Europe is definitely deadlocked.
With the euro crisis, Project Europe is officially dead.
Across Europe, parties opposing the EU or advocating for the abandonment of the euro as a common currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party, founded only this year and arriving from nowhere, garnered nearly five million votes in the September federal elections and pulled the Liberal Democratic Party (equivalent to our Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been national opposition to the project of creating a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has marked a turning point.
The austerity imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, coupled with the burden on national economies through membership of the single currency, has led many people to think that Project Europe has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments having excessive budget deficits – this was only true for Greece.
Instead, the European system has put a strain on its members with exchange rates favorable to German exporters – which German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of a devaluation of the national currency, the countries of southern Europe find themselves with an intrinsic productivity problem vis-<0xC3><0xA0>-vis Germany.
The only recourse is to make dark cuts in wages and public spending – encouraged by Berlin.
Beyond the current fiscal and monetary problems, there is a deeper malaise linked to productivity in Europe.
Following the “green” energy policies imposed by Brussels – which are a reason to subsidize French and German energy companies at the expense of the consumer – European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas as the United States.
This is a costly disadvantage, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
Not all wage freezes in the world will prevent the European petrochemical industry from being penalized by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, the revolt is rumbled, especially in France, one of the great leaders of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needed Paris as a passport to its political legitimacy and imposed its own economic policy on Europe, leaving the French economy struggling.
As a result, Marine Le Pen’s far-right anti-European National Front party has just won a crucial by-election, putting socialists in power in third place.
The National Front is now the most popular party in France with 24% of the vote – a timely warning to the British Labour Party that it cannot assume that a split of the right will automatically favor the left.
What does Marine Le Pen do with her new popularity with the French white working class?
It wants to use next year’s European elections to create a single anti-currency and anti-European bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-European parties do well in these elections, which is very possible, such a bloc could control the European Parliament for the first time.
This is what I think: very soon, anti-European and anti-currency sentiment in Europe will unite and eventually kill the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will come back to something that will look more like the free “Europe of (Sovereign) Nations” favoured by General de Gaulle.
Germany and some of its satellite economies could keep the euro, but France and southern Europe will regain their own currency.
I expect the United Kingdom to distance itself from this project, and I hope it will keep its eyes on the United States.
However, Washington's growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be left behind in the Atlantic.
What about Scotland in all of this?
We can decide to be a region of little England (essentially).
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which includes sending Berlin and Brussels out for a walk.
