Currently, passengers must turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the doors of the plane are closed.
They are not expected to restart them until the aircraft reaches an altitude of 10,000 feet and the commander gives the green light.
Passengers are supposed to turn off their aircraft when the aircraft descends before landing and not turn them on again until the aircraft has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are properly protected from electronic interference will be able to allow passengers to use their aircraft during take-offs, landings and grounding, the FAA said.
Most new airliners and other aircraft that have been modified so that passengers can use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Association of Professional Flight Attendants, said she was pleased with the changes.
“Once the new policy is implemented safely – and we will work closely with carriers to do so – it will benefit everyone,” Glading said in a statement.
