Is the European elite ready to do business with Britain?
The Business for Britain campaign was launched in April with the promise to bring businesses together and define what wealth and jobs creators want to see change in our relationship with the EU.
To do this, we commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey of UK business leaders and asked them what they thought of Britain, businesses and the EU.
YouGov surveyed more than 1,000 business leaders, globally representative of all business sizes, sectors and regions in Britain.
The findings of the investigation will come as a surprise to many.
We found that the vast majority of companies are now looking to export outside Europe, focusing on countries that are modernising and growing while EU states are stagnating.
They want the government to prioritize new trade ties with countries like China, India and Brazil rather than get bogged down in the long and arduous process of reforming Europe’s institutional arcana.
When asked for their views on specific policy issues – ranging from monopolies regulation to product laws – the majority of business leaders believe that control of these key competencies should return to Westminster.
The single market has caused general dissatisfaction, with companies saying that the cost of the Brussels regulation is disproportionate to the benefits of being part of the European trading area – 40% of large companies, traditionally the most pro-European, even agree.
Finally, and more importantly, our survey of business leaders revealed that a large majority wanted Britain to pursue initiatives in favour of a treaty change and the development of a relationship with the EU based on trade and not politics.
This conclusion, which is found in all major groups and companies of all sizes, shows that the corporate world insists on a “significant change” that restores power to the UK.
The stakes are high – achieving a treaty change and better representing Britain’s interests would see a 16% turnaround in favour of keeping the country in the EU in a referendum.
The Prime Minister should not hesitate for a moment: this investigation shows that British companies support this plan to renegotiate the terms of Britain’s EU membership.
It also shows that companies hope that renegotiation will represent a significant shift in the current balance of power in favour of a return to the UK.
It is possible, and increasingly necessary, to better represent the interests of British businesses, as the euro area embarks on a path towards a closer economic and fiscal union.
