How Biometrics Will Invade Our Lives
No more passwords to enter to access his smartphone or pay for his purchases?
American, French or Japanese researchers predict a future where we will be recognized by the biometric sensors of phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, deputy general manager of Morpho, even believes that "the century will be biometric".
Only biometrics will be able to ascertain the identity of a person carrying out transactions in a universe as transversal and transnational as the Internet.
Privacy organizations are confirming this craze for biometrics, but are worried about it.
In 2011 and in France alone, the Commission Nationale de l'Informatique et des Libertés authorized 774 systems for the recognition of fingerprints, the shape of the hand or the venous network of the hand in companies, administrations, canteens...
“Everyone will soon be able to be identified, anywhere and anytime,” said Justin Brookman, head of consumer privacy at the Center for Democracy and Technology in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism, among some, and pessimism, among others?
Biometrics will be based on new techniques, which will provide new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most used biometric data are fingerprints, the contour of the hand and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its own constraints.
"For example, some people who work with concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are unreadable," says Philippe Robin, technical director of the identity field at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection as well as the verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand assume a voluntary and precise gesture of people.
This is both a security - it is not possible to capture this data without their knowledge - and a disadvantage: sometimes the procedure must be repeated and therefore takes time.
As a result, research has been conducted for the past 20 years on other approaches, such as facial or iris recognition (the colored part of the eye).
Thanks to the increased accuracy of the sensors and the computing capacity of the computers required for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has increased tenfold over the past five years, says Cyrille Bataller, director of Accenture’s R&D labs in Europe.
With our help, the UK and the Netherlands have deployed automatic border crossings using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
“Today, we’re doing research on voice recognition or how to walk using sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment,” said Sridhar Iyengar, director of security research at Intel Labs.
A unique and unfalsifiable marker, DNA also raises hopes and concerns.
"In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered the ultimate biometric data," confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Foresight at the CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very time-consuming and very expensive.
NEC offers forensic services a suitcase costing 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples at the scene of a crime and in one hour.
The uses of biometrics are divided into two groups: identification (recognizing one person among others) and authentication (ensuring that the person is who they claim to be).
The identification has hitherto concerned the issuance of identity cards: it is necessary to compare the biometric elements (prints, photo, iris) with the information that the State has on all citizens already registered.
This ensures that a person does not attempt to impersonate someone else.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or a store.
"We collect the images from the surveillance cameras and compare them to the photos of celebrities who circulate freely on the Internet," explains Dany Nassif, who is in charge of commercial development for biometric identification solutions at NEC France.
Another use: take a picture of a guy queuing in a store, track his progress through facial recognition, and calculate the wait time.
Authentication initially concerned physical access (borders, protected premises, canteens, etc.) or logical access (opening a computer).
More recently, presence checks have been added.
"One biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of the boyfriend pointing for another," explains Cyrille Bataller, from Accenture.
But, more and more, authentication will also concern transactions, especially those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from some vending machines by inserting your card and placing your hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces the hit of the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoul<0xC3><0xAA>me by the company Natural Security in partnership with banks and retailers: when paying in store with his credit card, the customer does not type his code, but inserts his finger in a reader that scans the veins.
The experiment is scheduled to last six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French merchants.
Tracks to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometrics appealing to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
“If, thanks to biometrics, a customer stays in the box 30 seconds less, that’s appreciable,” says the manager of a large area.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you customized options.
And, finally, reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect the databases.
“Fingerprints are stored on a first server; people’s identities are on a second basis: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure box, which locks if you try to move it,” says Philippe Robin, of Thales.
But, lacking in-depth studies, it is impossible to know if these speeches really convince users.
Privacy experts, however, continue to be concerned.
“Advanced facial recognition, the multiplication of surveillance cameras and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa, make me fear the worst: widespread surveillance,” said Andrew Patrick of the Office of the Privacy Commissioner of Canada.
