The election ended in a landslide victory and news anchors took the time to reflect on the historical nature of the moment.
My comrades wept for joy and my parents kept all the newspapers they found.
A young team of visionaries was advancing toward the White House and the nation was ready for change.
During Obama’s transitional period before he took office in 2008, he had 82% favorable views.
And then I close the book.
The return to the present is a difficult awakening, it is like getting out of a dream.
It is difficult to remember these days full of optimism, they are like distant memories, a sad reminder of the opportunities of the past.
The change really happened in the years that followed the first time I voted.
It had nothing to do with what I had imagined.
I credit Obama with great accomplishments, from the passage of the Affordable Care Act to the departure of our army from Iraq, to the end of the “never seen nor known” and the assassination of Osama bin Laden.
In addition, I believe that partisan obstructionism has destroyed too many efforts to advance our nation in the area of immigration reforms, public health care, and the closure of Guantanamo, among other things.
But after repeatedly defending the Obama administration against my peers and colleagues, I can no longer provide explanations.
I am on the brink of political despair.
The Republican obstruction cannot explain the wiretapping of foreign leaders, nor the drone attacks on innocent foreign children.
It cannot explain that the National Security Agency collects data on the privacy of Americans, nor the indictment of whistleblowers who reveal the wrongdoing of the government.
It cannot justify the assassination of Anwar al-Awlaki, a U.S. citizen, without trial, nor the evasion of public funding and the exceedance of authorized spending during presidential campaigns.
She can’t justify the findings of a report that says the White House’s efforts to silence the media are “the most aggressive ... since Nixon’s administration.”
And, more recently, it cannot excuse the impossibility of designing a simple website for more than three years after the Affordable Care Act was ratified.
I don't know if that's what I was expecting.
If, at 18, I was supposed to understand that governance could contradict the political campaigns that preceded it.
Obviously, the electoral function is not predictable, because the opposition political party and events that happen by chance, such as the Newton massacre, influence our public conversation.
However, all the examples I have listed above seem to be largely the choice of administration.
That's what bothers me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney presented a confusing and unrefined alternative that did not seem to determine his policies or positions.
I felt that Obama, elected for a second term by being freed from the pressure of future elections, would deliver on the promises that had been heard of for so long.
Yet, while the favorable opinion index has plunged below 45% this week, it is even more difficult to get back to 2008 through this book.
It makes me want the many promises that have flown.
This week, I read the part of the book that describes how Obama suffered huge losses to Clinton in the Pennsylvania Primaries.
At a post-campaign meeting, he told his team that they needed to get back on track and stay true to their cause.
“I want us to focus on our talent,” he said.
We need to remember who we are.
Five years later, Mr. President, I no longer agree with you.
The views expressed in this commentary are only those of Nathaniel Morris.
