A team of biologists led by the Wildlife Conservation Society of New York has identified a new species of humpback dolphin off the northern coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, Scientific Mission Officer at the Observatory for the Conservation and Study of Marine Animals and Environments (OCEAMM) returns to L'Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identifying new species.
Does the discovery of this new species of humpback dolphin surprise you?
That's good news, but I'm not particularly surprised.
If in the past species have been described and identified on a morphological, anatomical and geographical basis, today the development of new tools such as genetics allow us to improve our knowledge in the sciences of classification of species.
Moreover, it is not impossible that these advances in genetics and molecular biology call into question the classification or belonging of a species to a genus, a family, or even an order.
In the early 19th century, morphologists classified animals, based on morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these rankings are called into question due to advances in genetics.
In the same way, two species very close morphologically have been distinguished through genetics.
This is the case of the new species that has just been identified.
Ten years ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: Pacific humpback dolphins and Atlantic humpback whales.
Recent analyses have made it possible to distinguish four species.
Why is this a discovery of importance as claimed by the Wildlife Conservation Society?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences, in order to protect the species and therefore its genetic variability.
If this population was already known for a long time by researchers, they did not know that it was part of a new species, present only in this place.
Therefore, if a massive mortality problem caused by a viral epidemic or accidental capture arises in the region, we may be dealing with the extinction of a species, rather than a local extinction of a population of a species more widespread on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered endangered or endangered depending on the number of individuals on Earth, i.e. the stock, and the possibility of recovery from nearby stocks.
As for the species Sousa chinensis, whose population of the newly discovered species is derived, its stock has automatically become smaller, making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats, in which there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This mixing of genes limits the creation of new species.
Conversely, more closed ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can eventually lead to the creation of new species.
It should be noted that the marine environment is the least well-known.
We prefer to send robots to Mars, than to know what lives in the Mariana Trench, only 11 kilometers from the surface of the sea.
We spend more money on the search for life on other planets than we do on marine research, and it's time for that to change.
