Back in black and white for Marie Chouinard, who presents at Danse Danse her two new group choreographies: the first inspired by the inks and poems of Henri Michaux, the second inspired by the famous solo piano Gymnopédies by Satie.
An evening that allows you to see all the prism of Chouinard, from art to tics and from ink black to white.
A white screen serves as a background wall.
On the carpet, as white, in the immense space that is the Thé<0xC3><0xA2>tre Maisonneuve, advances, in profile, thin as a line and dressed in black, a body.
On the screen, an ink of Henri Michaux is projected.
The body, a simple trait, takes its form.
And this shape will be that of the whole room: a string of physical imitations of the drawings.
The dancers, fully dressed in black, only the hands and face uncovered, wait on either side of the playground, rush when the next handwriting appears, embody it, come out running.
This black and white game by Henri Michaux is made in solo relays, in group in unison (a mass that makes solo), in a large group of twelve solos where each performs his sign.
One thinks of "Morning Glory", where, solo, Chouinard performed a series of choreographic tasks written on posters, posed online in the foreground.
This is the same principle, giant PowerPoint version.
Here, the music is loud, percussion and electric guitars.
The energy is high, the pace is always fast.
There will be a break when Carol Prieur takes refuge under the dance mat, to deliver, microphone in hand, without sobriety or restraint, a part of Michaux’s poem, monotone and monotonous in the call, and will continue dancing.
And the music to go back, and the sequence to resume.
This sound and energetic discharge, long, if possible, ends up deafening and numbing.
As does the regularity of the visual rhythm.
There are some beautiful flashes – image-making has always been a force at Chouinard – like those hairs that are stunned or those black fabrics that stretch the lines.
But the choreographic approach lacks composition.
We have the impression that the choreographer, instead of going to meet the work of Michaux, has imposed herself, with her tics.
As a result, the bodies appear flat in front of the drawings.
Michaux’s inks, like Gestalt forms, open up a wider and giddy imaginary than dance, more porous.
Only the ending, in negative, with its dancers chopped by a strobe light and white signs in a suddenly black theater, touches magic.
The public liked it, the welcome was warm.
Gymnopedias, after the break, is richer.
The stage is partly draped in gray, the dancers and a piano are covered in fabrics, like furniture in an abandoned house.
At the piano, dancers take turns to play the scores.
Their clumsiness in music, touching, give a real fragility.
On stage, couples pass, in love duos, very sensual, even erotic.
Group work, small solos of transitions, moving ensembles, choirs, writing is less binary.
Buffoons appear, also familiar to Chouinard, wearing the red nose, in very polarized male-female love parades.
The lovers are carnassiers, fugitives or players.
The gestures, the laughter and the little cries beautifully transpose the archaic, the grace and the ridicule of bodies in coitus, of beings that merge.
But the piece takes its real flight after salvation.
A clown returns to the stage when the audience leaves.
There, everything becomes permissible: the fourth wall falls, the universes explored overlap, the dancers cabotage, descend among the spectators, gloss, smoke, short circuit, play codes of applause, stretch the sauce in a cleverly calculated disorder that remains sensual.
Joy and madness perspire, and it is Chouinard's art, there, to contaminate the public.
