John Kerry admitted, unprecedented fact, that American espionage “has gone too far inappropriately.”
John Kerry indicated a softening of the U.S. defensive attitude toward its surveillance programs by admitting, unprecedentedly, that on several occasions, espionage “has gone too far inappropriately.”
The Secretary of State also admitted that he, like Barack Obama, ruled on “autopilot” when a series of incendiary revelations by whistleblower Edward Snowden about NSA spying activities emerged.
The leaks have put the U.S. government at the center of a diplomatic storm with its allies.
Speaking at an intergovernmental conference in London via video link, Kerry said: "It is undeniable that the President, myself and other members of the government have been aware of certain things in autopilot mode because we had the opportunity, from the Second World War to the difficult years of the Cold War, and then of course on 9/11."
He then became the first high-ranking member of the U.S. government to admit that U.S. espionage had crossed the line, but insisted that everyone’s rights had not been violated.
He said: “In some cases, it went too far inappropriately.”
And the President is determined to try to clarify and make it clear to people that he is now undertaking a thorough review of these practices so that no one feels deceived.
I assure you that innocent people will not be abused in this process.
Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA was a force acting for good and that its surveillance operations had saved many lives.
He added: “We live in a new world where people are ready to get blown up.”
There is radical extremism in the world that is determined to try to kill people, blow them up and attack governments.
What if you could intercept their communications and stop them before they act?
We did prevent planes from falling, buildings from exploding and people from being killed because we were able to get to the facts in advance.
In the meantime, U.S. lawmakers will travel to Europe to address concerns about the alleged U.S. spying case and convince Europeans of the need to continue joint counter-terrorism efforts with the United States, the chairman of the Senate subcommittee on European affairs said on Thursday.
Sen. Chris Murphy of Connecticut said he spoke to members of the European Parliament and others this week and was concerned about the threats they had made about a possible withdrawal of anti-terrorist organizations because of the sense of frustration aroused by the National Security Agency's oversight.
“It is really important for the protection of national security in the United States that Europeans stand by us in mutual engagement in the fight against terrorism,” Murphy, a Democrat serving his first term, and chairman of the U.S. Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs, said in an interview from Washington.
And I’m going to go to Europe to make them understand that we must continue to work together to fight terrorism, despite the anger caused by NSA programs.
The press reports that the NSA has picked up millions of communications in Europe, which has undermined relations with some U.S. allies, however the agency’s director said this week that it was inaccurate and that it was a misunderstanding as it concerned metadata that NATO allies had collected and shared with the United States.
Other revelations have reported documents leaked by Snowden that the NSA intercepted data and communications from German Chancellor Angela Merkel’s mobile phone and those of 34 other heads of state.
The director of intelligence, James Clapper, justified the spying on the allies by stating that it was necessary and that it was a common practice on both sides.
In an atmosphere of turmoil, Murphy said his office was organizing a congressional trip, which is expected to take place this year, and that he hoped the delegation would include members of both parties and both chambers.
The names of the other participating legislators are expected to be announced in the coming days.
He indicated that the route remained to be defined.
Murphy said the purpose of this trip was to improve relationships, but also to show "affectionate firmness."
He explained that European heads of state must be honest with their citizens about the kind of spying programs they have been implementing themselves for years.
“We can change our surveillance programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, but they also need to understand that we are not the only ones in the world doing espionage,” Murphy said.
Kerry plans to travel to the Middle East and Poland this weekend to deal with the resentment generated by U.S. strategies in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as U.S. surveillance activities.
